# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: perfect-hashing
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:perfect-hashing/dynamic-perfect-hashing] In computer science, **dynamic perfect hashing** is a programming technique for resolving collisions in a hash table data structure.
[src:perfect-hashing/dynamic-perfect-hashing] While more memory-intensive than its hash table counterparts, this technique is useful for situations where fast queries, insertions, and deletions must be made on a large set of elements.
[src:perfect-hashing/dynamic-perfect-hashing] The problem of optimal static hashing was first solved in general by Fredman, Komlós and Szemerédi.
[src:perfect-hashing/dynamic-perfect-hashing] In their 1984 paper, they detail a two-tiered hash table scheme in which each bucket of the (first-level) hash table corresponds to a separate second-level hash table.
[src:perfect-hashing/dynamic-perfect-hashing] Keys are hashed twice—the first hash value maps to a certain bucket in the first-level hash table; the second hash value gives the position of that entry in that bucket's second-level hash table.
[src:perfect-hashing/dynamic-perfect-hashing] The second-level table is guaranteed to be collision-free (i.e. perfect hashing) upon construction.
[src:perfect-hashing/dynamic-perfect-hashing] Consequently, the look-up cost is guaranteed to be O(1) in the worst-case.
[src:perfect-hashing/dynamic-perfect-hashing] In the static case, we are given a set with a total of x entries, each one with a unique key, ahead of time.
[src:perfect-hashing/dynamic-perfect-hashing] Fredman, Komlós and Szemerédi pick a first-level hash table with size $s=2(x-1)$ buckets.
[src:perfect-hashing/dynamic-perfect-hashing] To construct, x entries are separated into s buckets by the top-level hashing function, where $s=2(x-1)$ .
[src:perfect-hashing/dynamic-perfect-hashing] Then for each bucket with k entries, a second-level table is allocated with $k^{2}$ slots, and its hash function is selected at random from a universal hash function set so that it is collision-free (i.e. a perfect hash function) and stored alongside the hash table.
[src:perfect-hashing/dynamic-perfect-hashing] If the hash function randomly selected creates a table with collisions, a new hash function is randomly selected until a collision-free table can be guaranteed.
[src:perfect-hashing/dynamic-perfect-hashing] Finally, with the collision-free hash, the k entries are hashed into the second-level table.
[src:perfect-hashing/dynamic-perfect-hashing] The quadratic size of the $k^{2}$ space ensures that randomly creating a table with collisions is infrequent and independent of the size of k, providing linear amortized construction time.
[src:perfect-hashing/dynamic-perfect-hashing] Although each second-level table requires quadratic space, if the keys inserted into the first-level hash table are uniformly distributed, the structure as a whole occupies expected $O(n)$ space, since bucket sizes are small with high probability.
[src:perfect-hashing/dynamic-perfect-hashing] The first-level hash function is specifically chosen so that, for the specific set of x unique key values, the total space T used by all the second-level hash tables has expected $O(n)$ space, and more specifically $T<s+4\cdot x$ .
[src:perfect-hashing/dynamic-perfect-hashing] Fredman, Komlós and Szemerédi showed that given a universal hashing family of hash functions, at least half of those functions have that property.
[src:perfect-hashing/dynamic-perfect-hashing] In the dynamic case, when a key is inserted into the hash table, if its entry in its respective subtable is occupied, then a collision is said to occur and the subtable is rebuilt based on its new total entry count and randomly selected hash function.
[src:perfect-hashing/dynamic-perfect-hashing] Because the load factor of the second-level table is kept low $1/k$ , rebuilding is infrequent, and the amortized expected cost of insertions is $O(1)$ .
[src:perfect-hashing/dynamic-perfect-hashing] Similarly, the amortized expected cost of deletions is $O(1)$ .
[src:perfect-hashing/dynamic-perfect-hashing] Additionally, the ultimate sizes of the top-level table or any of the subtables is unknowable in the dynamic case.
[src:perfect-hashing/dynamic-perfect-hashing] One method for maintaining expected $O(n)$ space of the table is to prompt a full reconstruction when a sufficient number of insertions and deletions have occurred.
[src:perfect-hashing/dynamic-perfect-hashing] By results due to Dietzfelbinger et al., as long as the total number of insertions or deletions exceeds the number of elements at the time of last construction, the amortized expected cost of insertion and deletion remain $O(1)$ with full rehashing taken into consideration.
[src:perfect-hashing/dynamic-perfect-hashing] The implementation of dynamic perfect hashing by Dietzfelbinger et al. uses these concepts, as well as lazy deletion, and is shown in pseudocode below.
[src:perfect-hashing/dynamic-perfect-hashing] During the insertion of a new entry *x* at *j*, the global operations counter, *count*, is incremented.
[src:perfect-hashing/dynamic-perfect-hashing] If *x* exists at *j*, but is marked as deleted, then the mark is removed.
[src:perfect-hashing/dynamic-perfect-hashing] If *x* exists at *j* or at the subtable *Tj*, and is not marked as deleted, then a collision is said to occur and the *j*th bucket's second-level table *Tj* is rebuilt with a different randomly selected hash function *hj*.
[src:perfect-hashing/dynamic-perfect-hashing] Deletion of *x* simply flags *x* as deleted without removal and increments *count*.
[src:perfect-hashing/dynamic-perfect-hashing] In the case of both insertions and deletions, if *count* reaches a threshold *M* the entire table is rebuilt, where *M* is some constant multiple of the size of S at the start of a new *phase*.
[src:perfect-hashing/dynamic-perfect-hashing] Here *phase* refers to the time between full rebuilds.
[src:perfect-hashing/dynamic-perfect-hashing] Note that here the -1 in "Delete(*x*)" is a representation of an element which is not in the set of all possible elements *U*.
[src:perfect-hashing/dynamic-perfect-hashing] A full rebuild of the table of *S* first starts by removing all elements marked as deleted and then setting the next threshold value *M* to some constant multiple of the size of *S*.
[src:perfect-hashing/dynamic-perfect-hashing] Finally, for each subtable *Tj* a hash function *hj* is repeatedly randomly chosen from *Hsj* until *hj* is injective on the elements of *Tj*.
[src:perfect-hashing/dynamic-perfect-hashing] The expected time for a full rebuild of the table of *S* with size *n* is O(*n*).
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] A **hash function** is any function that can be used to map data of arbitrary size to fixed-size values, though there are some hash functions that support variable-length output.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] The values returned by a hash function are called *hash values*, *hash codes*, (*hash/message*) *digests*, or simply *hashes*.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] The values are usually used to index a fixed-size table called a *hash table*.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] Use of a hash function to index a hash table is called *hashing* or *scatter-storage addressing*.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] Hash functions and their associated hash tables are used in data storage and retrieval applications to access data in a small and nearly constant time per retrieval.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] They require an amount of storage space only fractionally greater than the total space required for the data or records themselves.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] Hashing is a way to access data quickly and efficiently.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] Unlike lists or trees, it provides near-constant access time.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] It also uses much less storage than trying to store all possible keys directly, especially when keys are large or variable in length.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] Use of hash functions relies on statistical properties of key and function interaction: worst-case behavior is intolerably bad but rare, and average-case behavior can be nearly optimal (minimal collision).
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] Hash functions are related to (and often confused with) checksums, check digits, fingerprints, lossy compression, randomization functions, error-correcting codes, and ciphers.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] Although the concepts overlap to some extent, each one has its own uses and requirements and is designed and optimized differently.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] The hash function differs from these concepts mainly in terms of data integrity.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] Hash tables may use non-cryptographic hash functions, while cryptographic hash functions are used in cybersecurity to secure sensitive data such as passwords.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] In a hash table, a hash function takes a key as an input, which is associated with a datum or record and used to identify it to the data storage and retrieval application.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] The keys may be fixed-length, like an integer, or variable-length, like a name.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] In some cases, the key is the datum itself.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] The output is a hash code used to index a hash table holding the data or records, or pointers to them.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] A good hash function satisfies two basic properties: it should be very fast to compute, and it should minimize duplication of output values (collisions).
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] Hash functions rely on generating favorable probability distributions for their effectiveness, reducing access time to nearly constant.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] High table loading factors, pathological key sets, and poorly designed hash functions can result in access times approaching linear in the number of items in the table.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] Hash functions can be designed to give the best worst-case performance, good performance under high table loading factors, and in special cases, perfect (collisionless) mapping of keys into hash codes.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] Implementation is based on parity-preserving bit operations (XOR and ADD), multiply, or divide.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] A necessary adjunct to the hash function is a collision-resolution method that employs an auxiliary data structure like linked lists, or systematic probing of the table to find an empty slot.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] Hash functions are used in conjunction with hash tables to store and retrieve data items or data records.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] The hash function translates the key associated with each datum or record into a hash code, which is used to index the hash table.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] When an item is to be added to the table, the hash code may index an empty slot (also called a bucket), in which case the item is added to the table there.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] If the hash code indexes a full slot, then some kind of collision resolution is required: the new item may be omitted (not added to the table), or replace the old item, or be added to the table in some other location by a specified procedure.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] That procedure depends on the structure of the hash table.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] In *chained hashing*, each slot is the head of a linked list or chain, and items that collide at the slot are added to the chain.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] Chains may be kept in random order and searched linearly, or in serial order, or as a self-ordering list by frequency to speed up access.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] In *open address hashing*, the table is probed starting from the occupied slot in a specified manner, usually by linear probing, quadratic probing, or double hashing until an open slot is located or the entire table is probed (overflow).
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] Searching for the item follows the same procedure until the item is located, an open slot is found, or the entire table has been searched (item not in table).
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] Hash functions are also used to build caches for large data sets stored in slow media.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] A cache is generally simpler than a hashed search table, since any collision can be resolved by discarding or writing back the older of the two colliding items.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] Hash functions are an essential ingredient of the Bloom filter, a space-efficient probabilistic data structure that is used to test whether an element is a member of a set.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] A special case of hashing is known as geometric hashing or the *grid method*.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] In these applications, the set of all inputs is some sort of metric space, and the hashing function can be interpreted as a partition of that space into a grid of *cells*.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] The table is often an array with two or more indices (called a *grid file*, *grid index*, *bucket grid*, and similar names), and the hash function returns an index tuple.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] Hash tables are also used to implement associative arrays and dynamic sets.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] A good hash function should map the expected inputs as evenly as possible over its output range.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] That is, every hash value in the output range should be generated with roughly the same probability.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] The reason for this requirement is that the cost of hashing-based methods goes up sharply as the number of *collisions* — pairs of inputs that are mapped to the same hash value — increases.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] If some hash values are more likely to occur than others, then a larger fraction of the lookup operations will have to search through a larger set of colliding table entries.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] This criterion only requires the value to be *uniformly distributed*, not *random* in any sense.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] A good randomizing function is (barring computational efficiency concerns) generally a good choice as a hash function, but the converse need not be true.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] Hash tables often contain only a small subset of the valid inputs.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] For instance, a club membership list may contain only a hundred or so member names, out of the very large set of all possible names.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] In these cases, the uniformity criterion should hold for almost all typical subsets of entries that may be found in the table, not just for the global set of all possible entries.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] In other words, if a typical set of *m* records is hashed to *n* table slots, then the probability of a bucket receiving many more than *m*/*n* records should be vanishingly small.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] In particular, if *m* < *n*, then very few buckets should have more than one or two records.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] A small number of collisions is virtually inevitable, even if *n* is much larger than *m*—see the birthday problem.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] In special cases when the keys are known in advance and the key set is static, a hash function can be found that achieves absolute (or collisionless) uniformity.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] Such a hash function is said to be *perfect*.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] There is no algorithmic way of constructing such a function—searching for one is a factorial function of the number of keys to be mapped versus the number of table slots that they are mapped into.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] When testing a hash function, the uniformity of the distribution of hash values can be evaluated by the chi-squared test.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] This test is a goodness-of-fit measure: it is the actual distribution of items in buckets versus the expected (or uniform) distribution of items.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] where n is the number of keys, m is the number of buckets, and *b**j* is the number of items in bucket j.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] A ratio within one confidence interval (such as 0.95 to 1.05) is indicative that the hash function evaluated has an expected uniform distribution.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] Hash functions can have some technical properties that make it more likely that they will have a uniform distribution when applied.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] One is the strict avalanche criterion: whenever a single input bit is complemented, each of the output bits changes with a 50% probability.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] The reason for this property is that selected subsets of the keyspace may have low variability.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] For the output to be uniformly distributed, a low amount of variability, even one bit, should translate into a high amount of variability (i.e. distribution over the tablespace) in the output.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] Each bit should change with a probability of 50% because, if some bits are reluctant to change, then the keys become clustered around those values.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] If the bits want to change too readily, then the mapping is approaching a fixed XOR function of a single bit.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] Standard tests for this property have been described in the literature.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] The relevance of the criterion to a multiplicative hash function is assessed here.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] In data storage and retrieval applications, the use of a hash function is a trade-off between search time and data storage space.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] If search time were unbounded, then a very compact unordered linear list would be the best medium; if storage space were unbounded, then a randomly accessible structure indexable by the key-value would be very large and very sparse, but very fast.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] A hash function takes a finite amount of time to map a potentially large keyspace to a feasible amount of storage space searchable in a bounded amount of time regardless of the number of keys.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] In most applications, the hash function should be computable with minimum latency and secondarily in a minimum number of instructions.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] Computational complexity varies with the number of instructions required and latency of individual instructions, with the simplest being the bitwise methods (folding), followed by the multiplicative methods, and the most complex (slowest) are the division-based methods.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] Because collisions should be infrequent, and cause a marginal delay but are otherwise harmless, it is usually preferable to choose a faster hash function over one that needs more computation but saves a few collisions.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] Division-based implementations can be of particular concern because a division requires multiple cycles on nearly all processor microarchitectures.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] Division (modulo) by a constant can be inverted to become a multiplication by the word-size multiplicative-inverse of that constant.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] This can be done by the programmer, or by the compiler.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] Division can also be reduced directly into a series of shift-subtracts and shift-adds, though minimizing the number of such operations required is a daunting problem; the number of machine-language instructions resulting may be more than a dozen and swamp the pipeline.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] If the microarchitecture has hardware multiply functional units, then the multiply-by-inverse is likely a better approach.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] We can allow the table size *n* to not be a power of 2 and still not have to perform any remainder or division operation, as these computations are sometimes costly.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] For example, let *n* be significantly less than 2*b*.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] Consider a pseudorandom number generator function *P*(key) that is uniform on the interval [0, 2*b* − 1].
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] A hash function uniform on the interval [0, *n* − 1] is *n* *P*(key) / 2*b*.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] We can replace the division by a (possibly faster) right bit shift: *n P*(key) >> *b*.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] If keys are being hashed repeatedly, and the hash function is costly, then computing time can be saved by precomputing the hash codes and storing them with the keys.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] Matching hash codes almost certainly means that the keys are identical.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] This technique is used for the transposition table in game-playing programs, which stores a 64-bit hashed representation of the board position.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] A *universal hashing* scheme is a randomized algorithm that selects a hash function *h* among a family of such functions, in such a way that the probability of a collision of any two distinct keys is 1/*m*, where *m* is the number of distinct hash values desired—independently of the two keys.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] Universal hashing ensures (in a probabilistic sense) that the hash function application will behave as well as if it were using a random function, for any distribution of the input data.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] It will, however, have more collisions than perfect hashing and may require more operations than a special-purpose hash function.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] A hash function that allows only certain table sizes or strings only up to a certain length, or cannot accept a seed (i.e. allow double hashing) is less useful than one that does.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] A hash function is applicable in a variety of situations.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] A hash procedure must be deterministic—for a given input value, it must always generate the same hash value.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] In other words, it must be a function of the data to be hashed, in the mathematical sense of the term.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] This requirement excludes hash functions that depend on external variable parameters, such as pseudo-random number generators or the time of day.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] It also excludes functions that depend on the memory address of the object being hashed, because the address may change during execution (as may happen on systems that use certain methods of garbage collection), although sometimes rehashing of the item is possible.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] The determinism is in the context of the reuse of the function.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] For example, Python adds the feature that hash functions make use of a randomized seed that is generated once when the Python process starts in addition to the input to be hashed.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] The Python hash (SipHash) is still a valid hash function when used within a single run, but if the values are persisted (for example, written to disk), they can no longer be treated as valid hash values, since in the next run the random value might differ.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] It is often desirable that the output of a hash function have fixed size (but see below).
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] If, for example, the output is constrained to 32-bit integer values, then the hash values can be used to index into an array.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] Such hashing is commonly used to accelerate data searches.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] Producing fixed-length output from variable-length input can be accomplished by breaking the input data into chunks of specific size.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] Hash functions used for data searches use some arithmetic expression that iteratively processes chunks of the input (such as the characters in a string) to produce the hash value.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] In many applications, the range of hash values may be different for each run of the program or may change along the same run (for instance, when a hash table needs to be expanded).
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] In those situations, one needs a hash function which takes two parameters—the input data *z*, and the number *n* of allowed hash values.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] A common solution is to compute a fixed hash function with a very large range (say, 0 to 232 − 1), divide the result by *n*, and use the division's remainder.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] If *n* is itself a power of 2, this can be done by bit masking and bit shifting.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] When this approach is used, the hash function must be chosen so that the result has fairly uniform distribution between 0 and *n* − 1, for any value of *n* that may occur in the application.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] Depending on the function, the remainder may be uniform only for certain values of *n*, e.g. odd or prime numbers.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] When the hash function is used to store values in a hash table that outlives the run of the program, and the hash table needs to be expanded or shrunk, the hash table is referred to as a dynamic hash table.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] A hash function that will relocate the minimum number of records when the table is resized is desirable.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] What is needed is a hash function *H*(*z*,*n*) (where *z* is the key being hashed and *n* is the number of allowed hash values) such that *H*(*z*,*n* + 1) = *H*(*z*,*n*) with probability close to *n*/(*n* + 1).
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] Linear hashing and spiral hashing are examples of dynamic hash functions that execute in constant time but relax the property of uniformity to achieve the minimal movement property.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] Extendible hashing uses a dynamic hash function that requires space proportional to *n* to compute the hash function, and it becomes a function of the previous keys that have been inserted.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] Several algorithms that preserve the uniformity property but require time proportional to *n* to compute the value of *H*(*z*,*n*) have been invented.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] A hash function with minimal movement is especially useful in distributed hash tables.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] In some applications, the input data may contain features that are irrelevant for comparison purposes.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] For example, when looking up a personal name, it may be desirable to ignore the distinction between upper and lower case letters.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] For such data, one must use a hash function that is compatible with the data equivalence criterion being used: that is, any two inputs that are considered equivalent must yield the same hash value.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] This can be accomplished by normalizing the input before hashing it, as by upper-casing all letters.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] There are several common algorithms for hashing integers.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] The method giving the best distribution is data-dependent.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] One of the simplest and most common methods in practice is the modulo division method.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] If the data to be hashed is small enough, then one can use the data itself (reinterpreted as an integer) as the hashed value.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] The cost of computing this *identity* hash function is effectively zero.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] This hash function is perfect, as it maps each input to a distinct hash value.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] The meaning of "small enough" depends on the size of the type that is used as the hashed value.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] For example, in Java, the hash code is a 32-bit integer.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] Thus the 32-bit integer `Integer` and 32-bit floating-point `Float` objects can simply use the value directly, whereas the 64-bit integer `Long` and 64-bit floating-point `Double` cannot.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] Other types of data can also use this hashing scheme.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] For example, when mapping character strings between upper and lower case, one can use the binary encoding of each character, interpreted as an integer, to index a table that gives the alternative form of that character ("A" for "a", "8" for "8", etc.).
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] If each character is stored in 8 bits (as in extended ASCII or ISO Latin 1), the table has only 28 = 256 entries; in the case of Unicode characters, the table would have 17 × 216 = 1114112 entries.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] The same technique can be used to map two-letter country codes like "us" or "za" to country names (262 = 676 table entries), 5-digit ZIP codes like 13083 to city names (100000 entries), etc.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] Invalid data values (such as the country code "xx" or the ZIP code 00000) may be left undefined in the table or mapped to some appropriate "null" value.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] If the keys are uniformly or sufficiently uniformly distributed over the key space, so that the key values are essentially random, then they may be considered to be already "hashed".
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] In this case, any number of any bits in the key may be extracted and collated as an index into the hash table.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] For example, a simple hash function might mask off the m least significant bits and use the result as an index into a hash table of size 2*m*.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] A mid-squares hash code is produced by squaring the input and extracting an appropriate number of middle digits or bits.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] For example, if the input is 123456789 and the hash table size 10000, then squaring the key produces 15241578750190521, so the hash code is taken as the middle 4 digits of the 17-digit number (ignoring the high digit) 8750.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] The mid-squares method produces a reasonable hash code if there is not a lot of leading or trailing zeros in the key.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] This is a variant of multiplicative hashing, but not as good because an arbitrary key is not a good multiplier.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] A standard technique is to use a modulo function on the key, by selecting a divisor M which is a prime number close to the table size, so *h*(*K*) ≡ *K* (mod *M*).
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] This gives a distribution from {0, *M* − 1}.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] This gives good results over a large number of key sets.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] A significant drawback of division hashing is that division requires multiple cycles on most modern architectures (including x86) and can be 10 times slower than multiplication.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] A second drawback is that it will not break up clustered keys.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] This technique works well in practice because many key sets are sufficiently random already, and the probability that a key set will be cyclical by a large prime number is small.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] Algebraic coding is a variant of the division method of hashing which uses division by a polynomial modulo 2 instead of an integer to map n bits to m bits.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] If *Z*(*x*) is constructed to have t or fewer non-zero coefficients, then keys which share fewer than t bits are guaranteed to not collide.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] Z is a function of k, t, and n (the last of which is a divisor of 2*k* − 1) and is constructed from the finite field GF(2*k*).
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] Define $P(x)=\prod _{j\in S}(x-\alpha ^{j})$ where α ∈*n* GF(2*k*) and where the coefficients of *P*(*x*) are computed in this field.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] Since α2*j* is a root of *P*(*x*) whenever α*j* is a root, it follows that the coefficients *pi* of *P*(*x*) satisfy *p*2 *i* = *p*i, so they are all 0 or 1.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] If *R*(*x*) = *r**n*−1*x**n*−1 + ⋯ + *r*1*x* + *r*0 is any nonzero polynomial modulo 2 with at most t nonzero coefficients, then *R*(*x*) is not a multiple of *P*(*x*) modulo 2.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] If follows that the corresponding hash function will map keys with fewer than t bits in common to unique indices.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] The usual outcome is that either n will get large, or t will get large, or both, for the scheme to be computationally feasible.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] Therefore, it is more suited to hardware or microcode implementation.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] Unique permutation hashing has a guaranteed best worst-case insertion time.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] Standard multiplicative hashing uses the formula *h**a*(*K*) = ⌊(*aK* mod *W*) / (*W*/*M*)⌋, which produces a hash value in {0, …, *M* − 1}.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] The value a is an appropriately chosen value that should be relatively prime to W; it should be large, and its binary representation a random mix of 1s and 0s.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] An important practical special case occurs when *W* = 2*w* and *M* = 2*m* are powers of 2 and w is the machine word size.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] and for fixed m and w this translates into a single integer multiplication and right-shift, making it one of the fastest hash functions to compute.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] Multiplicative hashing is susceptible to a "common mistake" that leads to poor diffusion—higher-value input bits do not affect lower-value output bits.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] A transmutation on the input which shifts the span of retained top bits down and XORs or ADDs them to the key before the multiplication step corrects for this.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] Fibonacci hashing is a form of multiplicative hashing in which the multiplier is 2*w* / ϕ, where w is the machine word length and ϕ (phi) is the golden ratio (approximately 1.618).
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] A property of this multiplier is that it uniformly distributes over the table space, blocks of consecutive keys with respect to any block of bits in the key.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] Consecutive keys within the high bits or low bits of the key (or some other field) are relatively common.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] The multiplier should be odd, so the least significant bit of the output is invertible modulo 2*w*.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] The last two values given above are rounded (up and down, respectively) by more than 1/2 of a least-significant bit to achieve this.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] Zobrist hashing was originally introduced as a means of compactly representing chess positions in computer game-playing programs.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] A unique random number was assigned to represent each type of piece (six each for black and white) on each space of the board.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] Thus a table of 64×12 such numbers is initialized at the start of the program.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] The random numbers could be any length, but 64 bits was natural due to the 64 squares on the board.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] A position was transcribed by cycling through the pieces in a position, indexing the corresponding random numbers (vacant spaces were not included in the calculation) and XORing them together (the starting value could be 0 (the identity value for XOR) or a random seed).
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] The resulting value was reduced by modulo, folding, or some other operation to produce a hash table index.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] The original Zobrist hash was stored in the table as the representation of the position.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] Later, the method was extended to hashing integers by representing each byte in each of 4 possible positions in the word by a unique 32-bit random number.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] Thus, a table of 28×4 random numbers is constructed.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] A 32-bit hashed integer is transcribed by successively indexing the table with the value of each byte of the plain text integer and XORing the loaded values together (again, the starting value can be the identity value or a random seed).
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] The natural extension to 64-bit integers is by use of a table of 28×8 64-bit random numbers.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] This kind of function has some nice theoretical properties, one of which is called *3-tuple independence*, meaning that every 3-tuple of keys is equally likely to be mapped to any 3-tuple of hash values.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] A hash function can be designed to exploit existing entropy in the keys.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] If the keys have leading or trailing zeros, or particular fields that are unused, always zero or some other constant, or generally vary little, then masking out only the volatile bits and hashing on those will provide a better and possibly faster hash function.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] Selected divisors or multipliers in the division and multiplicative schemes may make more uniform hash functions if the keys are cyclic or have other redundancies.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] When the data values are long (or variable-length) character strings—such as personal names, web page addresses, or mail messages—their distribution is usually very uneven, with complicated dependencies.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] For example, text in any natural language has highly non-uniform distributions of characters, and character pairs, characteristic of the language.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] For such data, it is prudent to use a hash function that depends on all characters of the string—and depends on each character in a different way.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] Simplistic hash functions may add the first and last *n* characters of a string along with the length, or form a word-size hash from the middle 4 characters of a string.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] This saves iterating over the (potentially long) string, but hash functions that do not hash on all characters of a string can readily become linear due to redundancies, clustering, or other pathologies in the key set.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] Such strategies may be effective as a custom hash function if the structure of the keys is such that either the middle, ends, or other fields are zero or some other invariant constant that does not differentiate the keys; then the invariant parts of the keys can be ignored.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] The paradigmatic example of folding by characters is to add up the integer values of all the characters in the string.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] A better idea is to multiply the hash total by a constant, typically a sizable prime number, before adding in the next character, ignoring overflow.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] Using exclusive-or instead of addition is also a plausible alternative.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] The final operation would be a modulo, mask, or other function to reduce the word value to an index the size of the table.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] The weakness of this procedure is that information may cluster in the upper or lower bits of the bytes; this clustering will remain in the hashed result and cause more collisions than a proper randomizing hash.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] ASCII byte codes, for example, have an upper bit of 0, and printable strings do not use the last byte code or most of the first 32 byte codes, so the information, which uses the remaining byte codes, is clustered in the remaining bits in an unobvious manner.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] The classic approach, dubbed the PJW hash based on the work of Peter J.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] Weinberger at Bell Labs in the 1970s, was originally designed for hashing identifiers into compiler symbol tables as given in the "Dragon Book".
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] This hash function offsets the bytes 4 bits before adding them together.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] When the quantity wraps, the high 4 bits are shifted out and if non-zero, xored back into the low byte of the cumulative quantity.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] The result is a word-size hash code to which a modulo or other reducing operation can be applied to produce the final hash index.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] Today, especially with the advent of 64-bit word sizes, much more efficient variable-length string hashing by word chunks is available.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] The final word, which may have unoccupied byte positions, is filled with zeros or a specified randomizing value before being folded into the hash.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] The accumulated hash code is reduced by a final modulo or other operation to yield an index into the table.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] Analogous to the way an ASCII or EBCDIC character string representing a decimal number is converted to a numeric quantity for computing, a variable-length string can be converted as *x**k*−1a*k*−1 + *x**k*−2a*k*−2 + ⋯ + *x*1*a* + *x*0.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] This is simply a polynomial in a radix *a* > 1 that takes the components (*x*0,*x*1,...,*x**k*−1) as the characters of the input string of length *k*.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] It can be used directly as the hash code, or a hash function applied to it to map the potentially large value to the hash table size.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] The value of *a* is usually a prime number large enough to hold the number of different characters in the character set of potential keys.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] Radix conversion hashing of strings minimizes the number of collisions.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] Available data sizes may restrict the maximum length of string that can be hashed with this method.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] For example, a 128-bit word will hash only a 26-character alphabetic string (ignoring case) with a radix of 29; a printable ASCII string is limited to 9 characters using radix 97 and a 64-bit word.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] However, alphabetic keys are usually of modest length, because keys must be stored in the hash table.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] Numeric character strings are usually not a problem; 64 bits can count up to 1019, or 19 decimal digits with radix 10.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] In some applications, such as substring search, one can compute a hash function *h* for every *k*-character substring of a given *n*-character string by advancing a window of width *k* characters along the string, where *k* is a fixed integer, and *n* > *k*.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] The straightforward solution, which is to extract such a substring at every character position in the text and compute *h* separately, requires a number of operations proportional to *k*·*n*.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] However, with the proper choice of *h*, one can use the technique of rolling hash to compute all those hashes with an effort proportional to *mk* + *n* where *m* is the number of occurrences of the substring.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] The hash function used for the algorithm is usually the Rabin fingerprint, designed to avoid collisions in 8-bit character strings, but other suitable hash functions are also used.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] Fuzzy hashing, also known as similarity hashing, is a technique for detecting data that is similar, but not exactly the same, as other data.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] This is in contrast to cryptographic hash functions, which are designed to have significantly different hashes for even minor differences.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] Fuzzy hashing has been used to identify malware and has potential for other applications, like data loss prevention and detecting multiple versions of code.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] Perceptual hashing is the use of a fingerprinting algorithm that produces a snippet, hash, or fingerprint of various forms of multimedia.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] A perceptual hash is a type of locality-sensitive hash, which is analogous if features of the multimedia are similar.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] This is in contrast to cryptographic hashing, which relies on the avalanche effect of a small change in input value creating a drastic change in output value.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] Perceptual hash functions are widely used in finding cases of online copyright infringement as well as in digital forensics because of the ability to have a correlation between hashes so similar data can be found (for instance with a differing watermark).
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] Worst case results for a hash function can be assessed two ways: theoretical and practical.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] The theoretical worst case is the probability that all keys map to a single slot.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] The practical worst case is the expected longest probe sequence (hash function + collision resolution method).
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] This analysis considers uniform hashing, that is, any key will map to any particular slot with probability 1/*m*, a characteristic of universal hash functions.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] While Knuth worries about adversarial attack on real time systems, Gonnet has shown that the probability of such a case is "ridiculously small".
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] His representation was that the probability of *k* of *n* keys mapping to a single slot is α*k* / (*e*α *k*!), where *α* is the load factor, *n*/*m*.
[src:perfect-hashing/hash-function] The term *hash* offers a natural analogy with its non-technical meaning (to chop up or make a mess out of something), given how hash functions scramble their input data to derive their output.
[src:perfect-hashing/perfect-hash-function] In computer science, a **perfect hash function** h for a set S is a hash function that maps distinct elements in S to a set of m integers, with no collisions.
[src:perfect-hashing/perfect-hash-function] In mathematical terms, it is an injective function.
[src:perfect-hashing/perfect-hash-function] Perfect hash functions may be used to implement a lookup table with constant worst-case access time.
[src:perfect-hashing/perfect-hash-function] A perfect hash function can, as any hash function, be used to implement hash tables, with the advantage that no collision resolution has to be implemented.
[src:perfect-hashing/perfect-hash-function] In addition, if the keys are not in the data and if it is known that queried keys will be valid, then the keys do not need to be stored in the lookup table, saving space.
[src:perfect-hashing/perfect-hash-function] Disadvantages of perfect hash functions are that S needs to be known for the construction of the perfect hash function.
[src:perfect-hashing/perfect-hash-function] Non-dynamic perfect hash functions need to be re-constructed if S changes.
[src:perfect-hashing/perfect-hash-function] For frequently changing S dynamic perfect hash functions may be used at the cost of additional space.
[src:perfect-hashing/perfect-hash-function] The space requirement to store the perfect hash function is in *O*(*n*) where *n* is the number of keys in the structure.
[src:perfect-hashing/perfect-hash-function] The important performance parameters for perfect hash functions are the evaluation time, which should be constant, the construction time, and the representation size.
[src:perfect-hashing/perfect-hash-function] A perfect hash function with values in a limited range can be used for efficient lookup operations, by placing keys from S (or other associated values) in a lookup table indexed by the output of the function.
[src:perfect-hashing/perfect-hash-function] One can then test whether a key is present in S, or look up a value associated with that key, by looking for it at its cell of the table.
[src:perfect-hashing/perfect-hash-function] Each such lookup takes constant time in the worst case.
[src:perfect-hashing/perfect-hash-function] With perfect hashing, the associated data can be read or written with a single access to the table.
[src:perfect-hashing/perfect-hash-function] The important performance parameters for perfect hashing are the representation size, the evaluation time, the construction time, and additionally the range requirement ${\frac {m}{n}}$ (average number of buckets per key in the hash table).
[src:perfect-hashing/perfect-hash-function] The evaluation time can be as fast as *O*(*1*), which is optimal.
[src:perfect-hashing/perfect-hash-function] The construction time needs to be at least *O*(*n*), because each element in S needs to be considered, and S contains n elements.
[src:perfect-hashing/perfect-hash-function] This lower bound can be achieved in practice.
[src:perfect-hashing/perfect-hash-function] The lower bound for the representation size depends on m and n.
[src:perfect-hashing/perfect-hash-function] Let *m* = (1+ε) *n* and h a perfect hash function.
[src:perfect-hashing/perfect-hash-function] A good approximation for the lower bound is $\log e-\varepsilon \log {\frac {1+\varepsilon }{\varepsilon }}$ Bits per element.
[src:perfect-hashing/perfect-hash-function] For minimal perfect hashing, ε = 0, the lower bound is log e ≈ 1.44 bits per element.
[src:perfect-hashing/perfect-hash-function] A perfect hash function for a specific set S that can be evaluated in constant time, and with values in a small range, can be found by a randomized algorithm in a number of operations that is proportional to the size of S.
[src:perfect-hashing/perfect-hash-function] The original construction of Fredman, Komlós & Szemerédi (1984) uses a two-level scheme to map a set S of n elements to a range of *O*(*n*) indices, and then map each index to a range of hash values.
[src:perfect-hashing/perfect-hash-function] If k is chosen randomly, this step is likely to have collisions, but the number of elements ni that are simultaneously mapped to the same index i is likely to be small.
[src:perfect-hashing/perfect-hash-function] The second level of their construction assigns disjoint ranges of *O*(*ni*2) integers to each index i.
[src:perfect-hashing/perfect-hash-function] It uses a second set of linear modular functions, one for each index i, to map each member x of S into the range associated with *g*(*x*).
[src:perfect-hashing/perfect-hash-function] As Fredman, Komlós & Szemerédi (1984) show, there exists a choice of the parameter k such that the sum of the lengths of the ranges for the n different values of *g*(*x*) is *O*(*n*).
[src:perfect-hashing/perfect-hash-function] Additionally, for each value of *g*(*x*), there exists a linear modular function that maps the corresponding subset of S into the range associated with that value.
[src:perfect-hashing/perfect-hash-function] Both k, and the second-level functions for each value of *g*(*x*), can be found in polynomial time by choosing values randomly until finding one that works.
[src:perfect-hashing/perfect-hash-function] The hash function itself requires storage space *O*(*n*) to store k, p, and all of the second-level linear modular functions.
[src:perfect-hashing/perfect-hash-function] Computing the hash value of a given key x may be performed in constant time by computing *g*(*x*), looking up the second-level function associated with *g*(*x*), and applying this function to x.
[src:perfect-hashing/perfect-hash-function] A modified version of this two-level scheme with a larger number of values at the top level can be used to construct a perfect hash function that maps S into a smaller range of length *n* + *o*(*n*).
[src:perfect-hashing/perfect-hash-function] A more recent method for constructing a perfect hash function is described by Belazzougui, Botelho & Dietzfelbinger (2009) as "hash, displace, and compress".
[src:perfect-hashing/perfect-hash-function] Here a first-level hash function g is also used to map elements onto a range of r integers.
[src:perfect-hashing/perfect-hash-function] An element *x* ∈ *S* is stored in the Bucket Bg(x).
[src:perfect-hashing/perfect-hash-function] Then, in descending order of size, each bucket's elements are hashed by a hash function of a sequence of independent fully random hash functions (Φ1, Φ2, Φ3, ...), starting with Φ1.
[src:perfect-hashing/perfect-hash-function] If the hash function does not produce any collisions for the bucket, and the resulting values are not yet occupied by other elements from other buckets, the function is chosen for that bucket.
[src:perfect-hashing/perfect-hash-function] If not, the next hash function in the sequence is tested.
[src:perfect-hashing/perfect-hash-function] To evaluate the perfect hash function *h*(*x*) one only has to save the mapping σ of the bucket index *g*(*x*) onto the correct hash function in the sequence, resulting in h(x) = Φσ(g(x)).
[src:perfect-hashing/perfect-hash-function] Finally, to reduce the representation size, the (σ(i))0 ≤ i < r are compressed into a form that still allows the evaluation in *O*(*1*).
[src:perfect-hashing/perfect-hash-function] This approach needs linear time in n for construction, and constant evaluation time.
[src:perfect-hashing/perfect-hash-function] The representation size is in *O*(*n*), and depends on the achieved range.
[src:perfect-hashing/perfect-hash-function] For example, with *m* = 1.23*n* Belazzougui, Botelho & Dietzfelbinger (2009) achieved a representation size between 3.03 bits/key and 1.40 bits/key for their given example set of 10 million entries, with lower values needing a higher computation time.
[src:perfect-hashing/perfect-hash-function] The space lower bound in this scenario is 0.88 bits/key.
[src:perfect-hashing/perfect-hash-function] The use of *O*(*n*) words of information to store the function of Fredman, Komlós & Szemerédi (1984) is near-optimal: any perfect hash function that can be calculated in constant time requires at least a number of bits that is proportional to the size of S.
[src:perfect-hashing/perfect-hash-function] For perfect hash functions, it is first assumed that the range of h is bounded by n as *m* = (1+ε) *n*.
[src:perfect-hashing/perfect-hash-function] Using a perfect hash function is best in situations where there is a frequently queried large set, S, which is seldom updated.
[src:perfect-hashing/perfect-hash-function] This is because any modification of the set S may cause the hash function to no longer be perfect for the modified set.
[src:perfect-hashing/perfect-hash-function] Solutions which update the hash function any time the set is modified are known as dynamic perfect hashing, but these methods are relatively complicated to implement.
[src:perfect-hashing/perfect-hash-function] A minimal perfect hash function is a perfect hash function that maps n keys to n consecutive integers – usually the numbers from 0 to *n* − 1 or from 1 to n.
[src:perfect-hashing/perfect-hash-function] A more formal way of expressing this is: Let j and k be elements of some finite set S.
[src:perfect-hashing/perfect-hash-function] Then h is a minimal perfect hash function if and only if *h*(*j*) = *h*(*k*) implies *j* = *k* (injectivity) and there exists an integer a such that the range of h is *a*..*a* + |*S*| − 1.
[src:perfect-hashing/perfect-hash-function] It has been proven that a general purpose minimal perfect hash scheme requires at least $\log _{2}e\approx 1.44$ bits/key.
[src:perfect-hashing/perfect-hash-function] Assuming that S is a set of size n containing integers in the range $[1,2^{o(n)}]$ , it is known how to efficiently construct an explicit minimal perfect hash function from S to $\{1,2,\ldots ,n\}$ that uses space $n\log _{2}e+o(n)$ bits and that supports constant evaluation time.
[src:perfect-hashing/perfect-hash-function] In practice, there are minimal perfect hashing schemes that use roughly 1.56 bits/key if given enough time.
[src:perfect-hashing/perfect-hash-function] A hash function is k-perfect if at most k elements from S are mapped onto the same value in the range.
[src:perfect-hashing/perfect-hash-function] The "hash, displace, and compress" algorithm can be used to construct k-perfect hash functions by allowing up to k collisions.
[src:perfect-hashing/perfect-hash-function] A minimal perfect hash function F is *order preserving* if keys are given in some order *a*1, *a*2, ..., *a**n* and for any keys *a**j* and *a**k*, *j* < *k* implies *F*(*a**j*) < F(*a**k*).
[src:perfect-hashing/perfect-hash-function] In this case, the function value is just the position of each key in the sorted ordering of all of the keys.
[src:perfect-hashing/perfect-hash-function] A simple implementation of order-preserving minimal perfect hash functions with constant access time is to use an (ordinary) perfect hash function to store a lookup table of the positions of each key.
[src:perfect-hashing/perfect-hash-function] This solution uses $O(n\log n)$ bits, which is optimal in the setting where the comparison function for the keys may be arbitrary.
[src:perfect-hashing/perfect-hash-function] However, if the keys *a*1, *a*2, ..., *a**n* are integers drawn from a universe $\{1,2,\ldots ,U\}$ , then it is possible to construct an order-preserving hash function using only $O(n\log \log \log U)$ bits of space.
[src:perfect-hashing/perfect-hash-function] Moreover, this bound is known to be optimal.
[src:perfect-hashing/perfect-hash-function] While well-dimensioned hash tables have amortized average O(1) time (amortized average constant time) for lookups, insertions, and deletion, most hash table algorithms suffer from possible worst-case times that take much longer.
[src:perfect-hashing/perfect-hash-function] A worst-case O(1) time (constant time even in the worst case) would be better for many applications (including network router and memory caches).
[src:perfect-hashing/perfect-hash-function] Few hash table algorithms support worst-case O(1) lookup time (constant lookup time even in the worst case).
[src:perfect-hashing/perfect-hash-function] The few that do include: perfect hashing; dynamic perfect hashing; cuckoo hashing; hopscotch hashing; and extendible hashing.
[src:perfect-hashing/perfect-hash-function] A simple alternative to perfect hashing, which also allows dynamic updates, is cuckoo hashing.
[src:perfect-hashing/perfect-hash-function] This scheme maps keys to two or more locations within a range (unlike perfect hashing which maps each key to a single location) but does so in such a way that the keys can be assigned one-to-one to locations to which they have been mapped.
[src:perfect-hashing/perfect-hash-function] Lookups with this scheme are slower, because multiple locations must be checked, but nevertheless take constant worst-case time.
[src:perfect-hashing/static-hashing] Since static hashing requires that the database, its objects, and reference remain the same, its applications are limited.
[src:perfect-hashing/static-hashing] Databases which contain information which changes rarely are also eligible as it would only require a full rehash of the entire database on rare occasion.
[src:perfect-hashing/static-hashing] Examples of this include sets of words and definitions of specific languages, sets of significant data for an organization's personnel, etc.
[src:perfect-hashing/static-hashing] Perfect hashing is a model of hashing in which any set of n elements can be stored in a hash table of equal size and can have lookups done in constant time.
[src:perfect-hashing/static-hashing] It was specifically discovered and discussed by Fredman, Komlos and Szemeredi (1984) and has therefore been nicknamed "FKS hashing".
[src:perfect-hashing/static-hashing] FKS hashing makes use of a hash table with two levels in which the top level contains n buckets which each contain their own hash table.
[src:perfect-hashing/static-hashing] FKS hashing requires that if collisions occur they must do so only on the top level.
[src:perfect-hashing/static-hashing] The top level contains a randomly created hash function, $h(x)$ , which fits within the constraints of a Carter and Wegman hash function from universal hashing.
[src:perfect-hashing/static-hashing] Having done so the top level shall contain n buckets labeled $k_{1},k_{2},k_{3},...,k_{n}$ .
[src:perfect-hashing/static-hashing] Following this pattern, all of the buckets hold a hash table of size $s_{i}$ and a respective hash function $h_{i}(x)$ .
[src:perfect-hashing/static-hashing] The hash function will be decided by setting $s_{i}$ to $k_{i}^{2}$ and randomly going through functions until there are no collisions.
[src:perfect-hashing/static-hashing] Because there are $n \choose 2$ pairs of elements, of which have a probability of collision equal to $1/n$ , FKS hashing can expect to have strictly less than $n/2$ collisions.
[src:perfect-hashing/static-hashing] Based on this fact and that each $h(x)$ was selected so that the number of collisions would be at most $n/2$ , the size of each table on the lower level will be no greater than $2n$ .
[src:perfect-hashing/tabulation-hashing] In computer science, **tabulation hashing** is a method for constructing universal families of hash functions by combining table lookup with exclusive or operations.
[src:perfect-hashing/tabulation-hashing] It was first studied in the form of Zobrist hashing for computer games; later work by Carter and Wegman extended this method to arbitrary fixed-length keys.
[src:perfect-hashing/tabulation-hashing] Generalizations of tabulation hashing have also been developed that can handle variable-length keys such as text strings.
[src:perfect-hashing/tabulation-hashing] Despite its simplicity, tabulation hashing has strong theoretical properties that distinguish it from some other hash functions.
[src:perfect-hashing/tabulation-hashing] In particular, it is 3-independent: every 3-tuple of keys is equally likely to be mapped to any 3-tuple of hash values.
[src:perfect-hashing/tabulation-hashing] More sophisticated but slower variants of tabulation hashing extend the method to higher degrees of independence.
[src:perfect-hashing/tabulation-hashing] Because of its high degree of independence, tabulation hashing is usable with hashing methods that require a high-quality hash function, including hopscotch hashing, cuckoo hashing, and the MinHash technique for estimating the size of set intersections.
[src:perfect-hashing/tabulation-hashing] First, divide the key to be hashed into smaller "blocks" of a chosen length.
[src:perfect-hashing/tabulation-hashing] Then, create a set of lookup tables, one for each block, and fill them with random values.
[src:perfect-hashing/tabulation-hashing] Finally, use the tables to compute a hash value for each block, and combine all of these hashes into a final hash value using the bitwise exclusive or operation.
[src:perfect-hashing/tabulation-hashing] Let *p* be the number of bits in a key to be hashed, and *q* be the number of bits desired in an output hash function.
[src:perfect-hashing/tabulation-hashing] Choose a block size *r* ≤ *p*; the choice of block size controls the tradeoff between time and memory usage, so it should be made so that the tables are not too large, e.g., so that the tables fit into the computer's cache memory.
[src:perfect-hashing/tabulation-hashing] Smaller blocks use less memory but slow down the hash function.
[src:perfect-hashing/tabulation-hashing] Compute *t* = ceil(*p*/*r*), the number of *r*-bit blocks needed to represent a key.
[src:perfect-hashing/tabulation-hashing] Create a two-dimensional 2*r* × *t* array, *T*, and fill it with random *q*-bit numbers.
[src:perfect-hashing/tabulation-hashing] Now *T* can be used to compute the hash value *h*(*x*) of any given key *x*.
[src:perfect-hashing/tabulation-hashing] To do so, partition *x* into *r*-bit values, where *x*0 consists of the lowest *r* bits of *x*, *x*1 consists of the next *r* bits, etc.
[src:perfect-hashing/tabulation-hashing] For example, if *r* = 8, then *x**i* is just the *i*th byte of *x*.
[src:perfect-hashing/tabulation-hashing] Note that it is not valid to use the same table (e.g.
[src:perfect-hashing/tabulation-hashing] *T[0]*) for each *x*i, since then the hash function would not be able to distinguish between strings with the same *x*is, but permuted differently.
[src:perfect-hashing/tabulation-hashing] Code for a typical example with *r* = *t* = 8 and *q* = *p* = 64 is given below.
[src:perfect-hashing/tabulation-hashing] The first instance of tabulation hashing is Zobrist hashing, a method for hashing positions in abstract board games such as chess named after Albert Lindsey Zobrist, who published it in 1970.
[src:perfect-hashing/tabulation-hashing] In this method, a random bitstring is generated for each game feature such as a combination of a chess piece and a square of the chessboard.
[src:perfect-hashing/tabulation-hashing] Then, to hash any game position, the bitstrings for the features of that position are combined by a bitwise exclusive or.
[src:perfect-hashing/tabulation-hashing] The resulting hash value can then be used as an index into a transposition table.
[src:perfect-hashing/tabulation-hashing] Because each move typically changes only a small number of game features, the Zobrist value of the position after a move can be updated quickly from the value of the position before the move, without needing to loop over all of the features of the position.
[src:perfect-hashing/tabulation-hashing] Tabulation hashing in greater generality, for arbitrary binary values, was later rediscovered by Carter & Wegman (1979) and studied in more detail by Pătraşcu & Thorup (2012).
[src:perfect-hashing/tabulation-hashing] Carter & Wegman (1979) define a randomized scheme for generating hash functions to be universal if, for any two keys, the probability that they collide (that is, they are mapped to the same value as each other) is 1/*m*, where *m* is the number of values that the keys can take on.
[src:perfect-hashing/tabulation-hashing] They defined a stronger property in the subsequent paper Wegman & Carter (1981): a randomized scheme for generating hash functions is *k*-independent if, for every *k*-tuple of keys, and each possible *k*-tuple of values, the probability that those keys are mapped to those values is 1/*m**k*.
[src:perfect-hashing/tabulation-hashing] 2-independent hashing schemes are automatically universal, and any universal hashing scheme can be converted into a 2-independent scheme by storing a random number *x* as part of the initialization phase of the algorithm and adding *x* to each hash value.
[src:perfect-hashing/tabulation-hashing] Thus, universality is essentially the same as 2-independence.
[src:perfect-hashing/tabulation-hashing] However, *k*-independence for larger values of *k* is a stronger property, held by fewer hashing algorithms.
[src:perfect-hashing/tabulation-hashing] As Pătraşcu & Thorup (2012) observe, tabulation hashing is 3-independent but not 4-independent.
[src:perfect-hashing/tabulation-hashing] For any single key *x*, *T*[*x*0,0] is equally likely to take on any hash value, and the exclusive or of *T*[*x*0,0] with the remaining table values does not change this property.
[src:perfect-hashing/tabulation-hashing] Similarly, for any three keys *x*, *y*, and *z*, at least one of the three keys has a position *i* where its value *z**i* differs from the other two, so that even after the values of *h*(*x*) and *h*(*y*) are determined, *h*(*z*) is equally likely to be any valid hash value.
[src:perfect-hashing/tabulation-hashing] However, this reasoning breaks down for four keys because there are sets of keys *w*, *x*, *y*, and *z* where none of the four has a byte value that it does not share with at least one of the other keys.
[src:perfect-hashing/tabulation-hashing] For instance, if the keys have two bytes each, and *w*, *x*, *y*, and *z* are the four keys that have either zero or one as their byte values, then each byte value in each position is shared by exactly two of the four keys.
[src:perfect-hashing/tabulation-hashing] For these four keys, the hash values computed by tabulation hashing will always satisfy the equation *h*(*w*) ⊕ *h*(*x*) ⊕ *h*(*y*) ⊕ *h*(*z*) = 0, whereas for a 4-independent hashing scheme the same equation would only be satisfied with probability 1/*m*.
[src:perfect-hashing/tabulation-hashing] Therefore, tabulation hashing is not 4-independent.
[src:perfect-hashing/tabulation-hashing] Because tabulation hashing is a universal hashing scheme, it can be used in any hashing-based algorithm in which universality is sufficient.
[src:perfect-hashing/tabulation-hashing] For instance, in hash chaining, the expected time per operation is proportional to the sum of collision probabilities, which is the same for any universal scheme as it would be for truly random hash functions, and is constant whenever the load factor of the hash table is constant.
[src:perfect-hashing/tabulation-hashing] Therefore, tabulation hashing can be used to compute hash functions for hash chaining with a theoretical guarantee of constant expected time per operation.
[src:perfect-hashing/tabulation-hashing] However, universal hashing is not strong enough to guarantee the performance of some other hashing algorithms.
[src:perfect-hashing/tabulation-hashing] For instance, for linear probing, 5-independent hash functions are strong enough to guarantee constant time operation, but there are 4-independent hash functions that fail.
[src:perfect-hashing/tabulation-hashing] Nevertheless, despite only being 3-independent, tabulation hashing provides the same constant-time guarantee for linear probing.
[src:perfect-hashing/tabulation-hashing] Cuckoo hashing, another technique for implementing hash tables, guarantees constant time per lookup (regardless of the hash function).
[src:perfect-hashing/tabulation-hashing] Insertions into a cuckoo hash table may fail, causing the entire table to be rebuilt, but such failures are sufficiently unlikely that the expected time per insertion (using either a truly random hash function or a hash function with logarithmic independence) is constant.
[src:perfect-hashing/tabulation-hashing] With tabulation hashing, on the other hand, the best bound known on the failure probability is higher, high enough that insertions cannot be guaranteed to take constant expected time.
[src:perfect-hashing/tabulation-hashing] Nevertheless, tabulation hashing is adequate to ensure the linear-expected-time construction of a cuckoo hash table for a static set of keys that does not change as the table is used.
[src:perfect-hashing/tabulation-hashing] Although tabulation hashing as described above ("simple tabulation hashing") is only 3-independent, variations of this method can be used to obtain hash functions with much higher degrees of independence.
[src:perfect-hashing/tabulation-hashing] However, the number of table lookups needed to compute each hash value using Siegel's variation of tabulation hashing, while constant, is still too large to be practical, and the use of expanders in Siegel's technique also makes it not fully constructive.
[src:perfect-hashing/tabulation-hashing] Thorup (2013) provides a scheme based on tabulation hashing that reaches high degrees of independence more quickly, in a more constructive way.
[src:perfect-hashing/tabulation-hashing] Simple tabulation is limited to keys of a fixed length, because a different table of random values needs to be initialized for each position of a block in the keys.
[src:perfect-hashing/tabulation-hashing] Lemire (2012) studies variations of tabulation hashing suitable for variable-length keys such as character strings.
[src:perfect-hashing/tabulation-hashing] The general type of hashing scheme studied by Lemire uses a single table *T* indexed by the value of a block, regardless of its position within the key.
[src:perfect-hashing/tabulation-hashing] However, the values from this table may be combined by a more complicated function than bitwise exclusive or.
[src:perfect-hashing/tabulation-hashing] Lemire shows that no scheme of this type can be 3-independent.
[src:perfect-hashing/tabulation-hashing] Nevertheless, he shows that it is still possible to achieve 2-independence.
[src:perfect-hashing/tabulation-hashing] Mixed Tabulation hashing (and the less general Twisted Tabulation) were introduced by Dahlgaard and Thorup as a way to strengthen the properties of Tabulation hashing while keeping nearly the same performance.
[src:perfect-hashing/tabulation-hashing] Mixed tabulation can be seen as a xor'ing a "Double Tabulation" Thorup (2013) hash function with a simple tabulation hash function.
[src:perfect-hashing/tabulation-hashing] The idea is to pick a number d and hash to $2^{rd+q}$ bits rather than just $2^{q}$ .
[src:perfect-hashing/tabulation-hashing] This gives d new "derived characters" which are hashed by a second hash function and the two values are xor'ed together.
[src:perfect-hashing/tabulation-hashing] Mixed Tabulation was shown in 2016 to have strong concentration with regards to *k*-partitions, which are useful in algorithms for counting distinct elements, such as the classical method by Flajolet and Martin.
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] In mathematics and computing, **universal hashing** (in a randomized algorithm or data structure) refers to selecting a hash function at random from a family of hash functions with a certain mathematical property (see definition below).
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] This guarantees a low number of collisions in expectation, even if the data is chosen by an adversary.
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] Many universal families are known (for hashing integers, vectors, strings), and their evaluation is often very efficient.
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] Universal hashing has numerous uses in computer science, for example in implementations of hash tables, randomized algorithms, and cryptography.
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] Assume we want to map keys from some universe U into m bins (labelled $[m]=\{0,\dots ,m-1\}$ ).
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] The algorithm will have to handle some data set $S\subseteq U$ of $|S|=n$ keys, which is not known in advance.
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] Usually, the goal of hashing is to obtain a low number of collisions (keys from S that land in the same bin).
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] A deterministic hash function cannot offer any guarantee in an adversarial setting if $|U|>m\cdot n$ , since the adversary may choose S to be precisely the preimage of a bin.
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] This means that all data keys land in the same bin, making hashing useless.
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] Furthermore, a deterministic hash function does not allow for *rehashing*: sometimes the input data turns out to be bad for the hash function (e.g. there are too many collisions), so one would like to change the hash function.
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] The solution to these problems is to pick a function randomly from a family of hash functions.
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] In other words, any two different keys of the universe collide with probability at most $1/m$ when the hash function h is drawn uniformly at random from H .
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] This is exactly the probability of collision we would expect if the hash function assigned truly random hash codes to every key.
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] Sometimes, the definition is relaxed by a constant factor, only requiring collision probability $O(1/m)$ rather than $\leq 1/m$ .
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] This concept was introduced by Carter and Wegman in 1977, and has found numerous applications in computer science (see, for example).
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] If we have an upper bound of $\epsilon <1$ on the collision probability, we say that we have $\epsilon$ -almost universality.
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] So for example, a universal family has $1/m$ -almost universality.
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] Note that the definition of universality is only concerned with whether $h(x)-h(y)=0$ , which counts collisions.
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] The uniform difference property is stronger.
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] (Similarly, a universal family can be XOR universal if $\forall x,y\in U,~x\neq y$ , the value $h(x)\oplus h(y)~{\bmod {~}}m$ is uniformly distributed in $[m]$ where $\oplus$ is the bitwise exclusive or operation.
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] An even stronger condition is pairwise independence: we have this property when $\forall x,y\in U,~x\neq y$ we have the probability that $x,y$ will hash to any pair of hash values $z_{1},z_{2}$ is as if they were perfectly random: $P(h(x)=z_{1}\land h(y)=z_{2})=1/m^{2}$ .
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] Pairwise independence is sometimes called **strong universality**.
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] We say that a family is uniform if all hash values are equally likely: $P(h(x)=z)=1/m$ for any hash value z .
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] However, strong universality does imply uniformity.
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] Given a family with the uniform distance property, one can produce a pairwise independent or strongly universal hash family by adding a uniformly distributed random constant with values in $[m]$ to the hash functions.
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] For some applications (such as hash tables), it is important for the least significant bits of the hash values to be also universal.
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] When a family is strongly universal, this is guaranteed: if H is a strongly universal family with $m=2^{L}$ , then the family made of the functions $h{\bmod {2^{L'}}}$ for all $h\in H$ is also strongly universal for $L'\leq L$ .
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] Unfortunately, the same is not true of (merely) universal families.
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] For example, the family made of the identity function $h(x)=x$ is clearly universal, but the family made of the function $h(x)=x{\bmod {2^{L'}}}$ fails to be universal.
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] UMAC and Poly1305-AES and several other message authentication code algorithms are based on universal hashing.
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] In such applications, the software chooses a new hash function for every message, based on a unique nonce for that message.
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] Several hash table implementations are based on universal hashing.
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] In such applications, typically the software chooses a new hash function only after it notices that "too many" keys have collided; until then, the same hash function continues to be used over and over.
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] (Some collision resolution schemes, such as dynamic perfect hashing, pick a new hash function every time there is a collision.
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] Other collision resolution schemes, such as cuckoo hashing and 2-choice hashing, allow a number of collisions before picking a new hash function).
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] A survey of fastest known universal and strongly universal hash functions for integers, vectors, and strings is found in.
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] For any fixed set S of n keys, using a universal family guarantees the following properties.
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] The expected number of pairs of keys $x,y$ in S with $x\neq y$ that collide ( $h(x)=h(y)$ ) is bounded above by ${\binom {n}{2}}\cdot 1/m=n(n-1)/2m$ , which is of order $O(n^{2}/m)$ .
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] When the number of bins, m is chosen linear in n (i.e., is determined by a function in $\Omega (n)$ ), the expected number of collisions is $O(n)$ .
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] When hashing into $n^{2}$ bins, there are no collisions at all with probability at least a half.
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] The expected number of keys in bins with at least t keys in them is bounded above by $2n/(t-2(n/m)+1)$ .
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] Thus, if the capacity of each bin is capped to three times the average size ( $t=3n/m$ ), the total number of keys in overflowing bins is at most $O(m)$ .
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] This only holds with a hash family whose collision probability is bounded above by $1/m$ .
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] If a weaker definition is used, bounding it by $O(1/m)$ , this result is no longer true.
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] As the above guarantees hold for any fixed set S , they hold if the data set is chosen by an adversary.
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] However, the adversary has to make this choice before (or independent of) the algorithm's random choice of a hash function.
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] If the adversary can observe the random choice of the algorithm, randomness serves no purpose, and the situation is the same as deterministic hashing.
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] The second and third guarantee are typically used in conjunction with rehashing.
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] For instance, a randomized algorithm may be prepared to handle some $O(n)$ number of collisions.
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] If it observes too many collisions, it chooses another random h from the family and repeats.
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] Universality guarantees that the number of repetitions is a geometric random variable.
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] Since any computer data can be represented as one or more machine words, one generally needs hash functions for three types of domains: machine words ("integers"); fixed-length vectors of machine words; and variable-length vectors ("strings").
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] This section refers to the case of hashing integers that fit in machines words; thus, operations like multiplication, addition, division, etc. are cheap machine-level instructions.
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] Let the universe to be hashed be $\{0,\dots ,|U|-1\}$ , and let the range of the hash functions be ${0,\ldots ,n-1}$ .
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] where $a,b$ are randomly chosen integers modulo p with $a\neq 0$ .
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] for some integer i between 0 and $(p-1)/m$ .
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] Since $p\geq |U|$ , if $x\neq y$ their difference $x-y$ is nonzero and has an inverse modulo p .
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] There are $p-1$ possible choices for a (since $a=0$ is excluded) and, varying i in the allowed range, $\lfloor (p-1)/m\rfloor$ possible non-zero values for the right hand side.
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] Another way to see H is a universal family is via the notion of statistical distance.
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] Since $x-y$ is nonzero and a is uniformly distributed in $\{1,\dots ,p-1\}$ , it follows that $a(x-y)$ modulo p is also uniformly distributed in $\{1,\dots ,p-1\}$ .
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] The distribution of $(h(x)-h(y))~{\bmod {~}}m$ is thus almost uniform, up to a difference in probability of $\pm 1/p$ between the samples.
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] As a result, the statistical distance to a uniform family is $O(m/p)$ , which becomes negligible when $p\gg m$ .
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] The state of the art for hashing integers is the **multiply-shift** scheme described by Dietzfelbinger et al. in 1997.
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] By avoiding modular arithmetic, this method is much easier to implement and also runs significantly faster in practice (usually by at least a factor of four).
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] The scheme assumes the number of bins is a power of two, $m=2^{M}$ .
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] Let w be the number of bits in a machine word.
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] Then the hash functions are parametrised over odd positive integers $a<2^{w}$ (that fit in a word of w bits).
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] To evaluate $h_{a}(x)$ , multiply x by a modulo $2^{w}$ and then keep the high order M bits as the hash code.
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] This scheme does *not* satisfy the uniform difference property and is only *$2/m$ -almost-universal*; for any $x\neq y$ , $\Pr\{h_{a}(x)=h_{a}(y)\}\leq 2/m$ .
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] Assume that the least significant set bit of $x-y$ appears on position $w-c$ .
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] Since a is a random odd integer and odd integers have inverses in the ring $Z_{2^{w}}$ , it follows that $a(x-y){\bmod {2}}^{w}$ will be uniformly distributed among w -bit integers with the least significant set bit on position $w-c$ .
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] The probability that these bits are all 0's or all 1's is therefore at most $2/2^{M}=2/m$ .
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] On the other hand, if $c<M$ , then higher-order M bits of $a(x-y){\bmod {2}}^{w}$ contain both 0's and 1's, so it is certain that $h(x)\neq h(y)$ .
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] This analysis is tight, as can be shown with the example $x=2^{w-M-2}$ and $y=3x$ .
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] where a is a random positive integer with $a<2^{2w}$ and b is a random non-negative integer with $b<2^{2w}$ .
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] This requires doing arithmetic on $2w$ -bit unsigned integers.
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] This version of multiply-shift is due to Dietzfelbinger, and was later analyzed more precisely by Woelfel.
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] This section is concerned with hashing a fixed-length vector of machine words.
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] Interpret the input as a vector ${\bar {x}}=(x_{0},\dots ,x_{k-1})$ of k machine words (integers of w bits each).
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] If m is a power of two, one may replace summation by exclusive or.
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] In practice, if double-precision arithmetic is available, this is instantiated with the multiply-shift hash family of hash functions.
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] Initialize the hash function with a vector ${\bar {a}}=(a_{0},\dots ,a_{k-1})$ of random **odd** integers on $2w$ bits each.
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] It is possible to halve the number of multiplications, which roughly translates to a two-fold speed-up in practice.
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] If double-precision operations are not available, one can interpret the input as a vector of half-words ( $w/2$ -bit integers).
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] The algorithm will then use $\lceil k/2\rceil$ multiplications, where k was the number of half-words in the vector.
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] Thus, the algorithm runs at a "rate" of one multiplication per word of input.
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] The same scheme can also be used for hashing integers, by interpreting their bits as vectors of bytes.
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] In this variant, the vector technique is known as tabulation hashing and it provides a practical alternative to multiplication-based universal hashing schemes.
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] Strong universality at high speed is also possible.
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] Initialize the hash function with a vector ${\bar {a}}=(a_{0},\dots ,a_{k})$ of random integers on $2w$ bits.
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] The result is strongly universal on w bits.
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] Experimentally, it was found to run at 0.2 CPU cycle per byte on recent Intel processors for $w=32$ .
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] This refers to hashing a *variable-sized* vector of machine words.
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] If the length of the string can be bounded by a small number, it is best to use the vector solution from above (conceptually padding the vector with zeros up to the upper bound).
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] The space required is the maximal length of the string, but the time to evaluate $h(s)$ is just the length of s .
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] As long as zeroes are forbidden in the string, the zero-padding can be ignored when evaluating the hash function without affecting universality.
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] Note that if zeroes are allowed in the string, then it might be best to append a fictitious non-zero (e.g., 1) character to all strings prior to padding: this will ensure that universality is not affected.
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] Now assume we want to hash ${\bar {x}}=(x_{0},\dots ,x_{\ell })$ , where a good bound on $\ell$ is not known a priori.
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] A universal family proposed by treats the string x as the coefficients of a polynomial modulo a large prime.
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] This Rabin-Karp rolling hash is based on a linear congruential generator.
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] Above algorithm is also known as *Multiplicative hash function*.
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] In practice, the *mod* operator and the parameter *p* can be avoided altogether by allowing integer to overflow because it is equivalent to *mod* (*Max-Int-Value* + 1) in many programming languages.
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] However, using the non-prime $2^{n}$ modulus is prone to collisions with certain inputs, regardless of the value of *a*.
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] Below table shows values chosen to initialize *h* and a for some of the popular implementations.
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] Consider two strings ${\bar {x}},{\bar {y}}$ and let $\ell$ be length of the longer one; for the analysis, the shorter string is conceptually padded with zeros up to length $\ell$ .
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] A collision before applying $h_{\mathrm {int} }$ implies that a is a root of the polynomial with coefficients ${\bar {x}}-{\bar {y}}$ .
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] This polynomial has at most $\ell$ roots modulo p , so the collision probability is at most $\ell /p$ .
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] The probability of collision through the random $h_{\mathrm {int} }$ brings the total collision probability to ${\frac {1}{m}}+{\frac {\ell }{p}}$ .
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] Thus, if the prime p is sufficiently large compared to the length of strings hashed, the family is very close to universal (in statistical distance).
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] Other universal families of hash functions used to hash unknown-length strings to fixed-length hash values include the Rabin fingerprint and the Buzhash.
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] For instance, one applies vector hashing to each 16-word block of the string, and applies string hashing to the $\lceil k/16\rceil$ results.
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] Since the slower string hashing is applied on a substantially smaller vector, this will essentially be as fast as vector hashing.
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] One chooses a power-of-two as the divisor, allowing arithmetic modulo $2^{w}$ to be implemented without division (using faster operations of bit masking).
[src:perfect-hashing/universal-hashing] The NH hash-function family takes this approach.
